abstract: Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo brushed past Cynthia Nixon in Thursday’s Democratic contest. But other challengers benefited from the progressive fervor sweeping national politics.
snippet: Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo brushed past Cynthia Nixon in Thursday’s Democratic contest. But other challengers benefited from the progressive fervor sweeping national politics.
lead_paragraph: The Democratic primary between Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo and Cynthia Nixon was over in about the time it takes to watch an episode of “Sex and the City.” The Associated Press called the race 30 minutes after the polls closed, as soon as it became apparent that the governor, a two-term incumbent and a Queens native, had rolled up big margins in the five boroughs.

snippet: Mr. Cuomo overcame an insurgent challenge from Ms. Nixon to claim the Democratic nomination.
lead_paragraph: Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo took a decisive step toward a third term on Thursday, quelling a liberal rebellion by turning aside the insurgent challenge of Cynthia Nixon to claim the Democratic nomination in New York.

abstract: In its half-century on the air, “60 Minutes” has operated independently of the CBS News organization. Many at the show worry what will happen if the network takes more control.
snippet: In its half-century on the air, “60 Minutes” has operated independently of the CBS News organization. Many at the show worry what will happen if the network takes more control.
lead_paragraph: For decades, the headquarters of CBS News and the offices of “60 Minutes” have stood on opposite sides of a windswept block of Manhattan’s West 57th Street.

abstract: Gov. Jerry Brown spearheaded the conference, but the demonstrators outside called on him to stop oil drilling in the state.
snippet: Gov. Jerry Brown spearheaded the conference, but the demonstrators outside called on him to stop oil drilling in the state.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — They erected a mini oil rig, locked arms through oil drums and sat down on the street. “Keep it in the ground,” their banners read. “No more fossil fuels,” they chanted.

abstract: Attacked by Fox News pundits, Rudolph Giuliani and a presidential Twitter account, the special counsel sticks to a stoic approach.
snippet: Attacked by Fox News pundits, Rudolph Giuliani and a presidential Twitter account, the special counsel sticks to a stoic approach.
lead_paragraph: Since his appointment 16 months ago as special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III has granted no interviews and held no news conferences. The spokesman for his office is known around Washington as “Mr. No-Comment.” Even public sightings are rare: A photograph of Mr. Mueller at an airport gate, with Donald Trump Jr. in the background, went viral.

headline_main: Under Fire, Robert Mueller Has a Novel P.R. Strategy: Silence
headline_print_headline: Impugned and Disparaged, but in Reply He Says Nothing

abstract: Several federal judges have criticized New York City’s elite Special Fed unit for obstructionist tactics in defending police misconduct lawsuits.
snippet: Several federal judges have criticized New York City’s elite Special Fed unit for obstructionist tactics in defending police misconduct lawsuits.
lead_paragraph: In one case, lawyers for the City of New York missed several filing deadlines and disobeyed court orders. An angry federal judge said they had “blown off” instructions, which he said was “outrageous.”

headline_main: Brett Kavanaugh, Burt Reynolds, North Korea: Your Friday Briefing

abstract: The convoluted and baldly political history of “home rule,” the legal quirk that allows the state to make decisions for New York City.
snippet: The convoluted and baldly political history of “home rule,” the legal quirk that allows the state to make decisions for New York City.
lead_paragraph: Regardless of where you stand on banning plastic bags, regulating speeding cars near schools, or how to fix the subways, most New York City residents are probably asking the same question: Why are those decisions being made in Albany by the governor and the state Legislature instead of in City Hall by the mayor and the City Council?
